I"×<h2 id="1-setting-up-exocore-on-your-machine">1. Setting up Exocore on your Machine</h2>
<p>The exocore exists as both a Visual Studio Code template package and a workflow between Github and Netlify. Follow these steps to get setup:</p>
<ol>
  <li><a href="https://github.com/join">Create a Github account</a></li>
  <li>Select use this template on the <a href="https://github.com/hot-domme/exocore">the Exocore repo</a> to fork it your account</li>
  <li>Download forked repo to your computer by navigating to Code &gt; Download Zip</li>
  <li>Download <a href="https://code.visualstudio.com/Download">Visual Studio Code</a></li>
  <li>Open your newly forked repository in VS Code with File &gt; Open, and navigating to the downloaded folder</li>
  <li>Accept the prompts to trust the folder, and install the recommended extensions. Your Exocore is now ready to be edited locally.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="2-publishing-your-exocore-to-the-web-with-netlify">2. Publishing Your Exocore to the Web with Netlify</h2>
<p>Netlify is a platform that provides free hosting and subdomain services directly from Github repos, so it can be used to automatically publish your exocore as a website for no-cost.</p>

<ol>
  <li>Login to <a href="https://app.netlify.com/">Netlify.app</a> with your Github account</li>
  <li>Select <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">Add new site &gt; Import an existing project</code></li>
  <li>Connect again with your GitHub account, then select the GitHub repo from the list</li>
  <li>The site will take about 10 minutes to build for the first time. After that, new changes will go live within one minute.</li>
  <li>To change your subdomain, visit Domain settings and then Options &gt; Edit Site Name. You can also add your own custom domain if you own one.</li>
</ol>

<h2 id="3-saving-changes-to-the-cloud-with-github">3. Saving Changes to the Cloud with Github</h2>
<p>While youâ€™re working in VS Code, your work will be automatically saved. However, to publish the data to Github so that it propagates onto the web, youâ€™ll need to setup a git commit workflow.</p>

<p>If youâ€™re already familiar with git, itâ€™s the standard commit process that can be done on your terminal. If youâ€™re new to git and Github, the easiest process is <a href="https://joshuadull.github.io/GitHub-Desktop/02-getting-started/index.html">using GitHub Desktop</a>.</p>

<h2 id="4-configuring-your-exocore">4. Configuring your Exocore</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Navigate to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">/_config.yml</code> to change the Title and URL of your exocore.</li>
  <li>Navigate to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">/_data/user.yml</code> to change your username and profile picture.</li>
  <li>Navigate to <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">/styles.scss</code> to select between different themes.</li>
</ol>

<p>You can also <a href="">customize Visual Studio Code heavily to your preference</a>, including easily changing color themes.</p>

